Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog** — override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs` using `GetDeferral()`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — add `BackButtonBehavior` in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel or code-behind
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating above, so the guard still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is **required** for async checks (like `DisplayAlert`). Without it, navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents the navigation when the user taps "Stay".
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` triggers a programmatic `GoToAsync("..")`, which the `OnNavigating` guard intercepts via `ShellNavigationSource.Pop`.
- Expose `HasUnsavedChanges` as a public property on your page (or check via the BindingContext/ViewModel).
